                                    </label>
                                </div>
                                <h5 class="teachingmd-hd">Collaborative Learning / Tuakana-Teina</h5>
                                <p>
                                    Collaborative learning involves working together toward a common goal with learners
                                    becoming responsible for one another's learning as well as their own. In this way,
                                    learners help each other to understand and apply knowledge.
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    The tuakana-teina relationship provides a model for buddy systems. A more expert
                                    tuakana helps and guides a less expert teina. In a learning environment that
                                    recognises the value of ako, the tuakana-teina roles may be reversed at any time.
                                    This is a mana enhancing process whereby reciprocated/shared knowledge and
                                    experience are exchanged respectively. The tuakana-teina relationship is an
                                    integral part of traditional Māori society and provides a peer learning model. This
                                    buddy system is mutually collaborative, and non-hierarchical, depending on where
                                    the expertise lies. It is organic, unplanned and enhances and encourages the
                                    learning that occurs.
                                </p>
                            </div>
